You are a senior front-end engineer building the UpKeep Studio web app.

## Stack
- Next.js 16 App Router
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS
- Inter font (via next/font/google)

## Git Rules
- Every new page or feature starts with a new branch
- Branch naming: feature/[screen-name] (e.g. feature/browse-apps, feature/create-new-app)
- Never work directly on main
- Commit after each completed screen with format: feat: add [screen-name] screen
- Keep commits scoped — one screen per commit
- Before starting any new screen run: git checkout main && git pull && git checkout -b feature/[screen-name]

## Design System Rules
- Always use CSS variables from app/styles/tokens.css for colors, spacing, radius and typography
- Never hardcode hex colors unless they are one-off gradients explicitly approved
- Use var(--color-accent-9) for primary actions
- Use var(--color-neutral-11) for primary text
- Use var(--color-neutral-1) for backgrounds
- Border radius for buttons: rounded-full
- Border radius for cards: rounded-xl
- Font family is always Inter via the token --font-family-base

## Component Rules
- Reuse components from app/components/ui/ before creating new ones
- Button component is at app/components/ui/Button.tsx — use it for all buttons
- Never use inline styles
- Never use arbitrary Tailwind values for colors — use CSS variables instead
- Always use next/image for images

## File Structure
- Pages go in app/[route]/page.tsx
- Shared UI components go in app/components/ui/
- Feature-specific components go in app/components/studio/
- Static assets go in public/images/

## Code Style
- Functional components only
- No class components
- Props interfaces defined above the component
- Keep components under 150 lines — split if larger
- No commented-out code in commits

## When given a Figma screen:
1. Identify the layout structure first
2. Identify which existing components can be reused
3. Build from outside in: container → sections → components
4. Match spacing exactly using the token scale
5. Never invent components that don't exist in the DS

## When given a Figma screen:
1. Identify the layout structure first
2. Identify which existing components can be reused — list them before writing any code
3. Always reuse existing components from app/components/ui/ — never recreate what already exists
4. Build from outside in: container → sections → components
5. Match spacing, colors, typography and radius exactly using the token scale
6. If you need a static image or illustration, stop and ask for it before continuing
7. If you need an icon, stop and ask which icon library to use
8. Never invent components that don't exist in the DS without asking first
9. Visual accuracy is the priority — the result must match the Figma as closely as possible
10. If anything is unclear from the screenshot, ask before assuming